article.description: Deanna Nolan, who had missed the previous game with a strained hamstring, had 26 points, including a 3-pointer with 4.2 seconds in overtime that gave Detroit a 90-87 victory Sunday over visiting New York.
article.headline: All-Star guard sinks game-winning trey
article.linkText: Nolan returns with 26-point bang in OT Shock victory
article.story:
AUBURN HILLS, Mich. (AP) -- The Detroit Shock didn't even know whether All-Star guard Deanna Nolan would be ready to play Sunday night against the New York Liberty. They were very happy with the eventual decision. Nolan, who had missed the previous game with a strained hamstring, had 26 points, including a 3-pointer with 4.2 seconds in overtime that gave Detroit a 90-87 victory. "Our trainer told me she should go, and that they would let me know how long," Shock coach Bill Laimbeer said. "After about five minutes, they told me to let her keep going. There is no one better in this game at hitting a shot with time running out like that." Nolan hit the off-balance shot over Crystal Robinson as the shot clock expired. "I was just trying to get some separation and get something off," she said. "It was a pretty good look, but I didn't know if I had the right distance because I was falling back a little." Nolan's game-winner was her third of the season -- she also hit buzzer-beaters July 16 at Indiana and three days later in Cleveland. "Deanna is great at that because she is super athletic," said Barb Farris, who assisted on the winning basket. "She can jump over almost anyone, so she can always get the shot off." Robinson agreed with Farris about Nolan's athletic skills. "I was right in her face, and she just hit an unbelievable shot," she said. Robinson missed a 3-pointer at the other end, and Teresa Weatherspoon's desperation heave at the buzzer also missed. "This is very tough on our team," New York coach Richie Adubato said. "We've played four games in six days, and we laid our heart and soul on the floor and came up just short." Detroit clinched home-court advantage in the first round of the Eastern Conference playoffs with the win. New York is now 1 1/2 games out of the final playoff spot in the East. Elaine Powell started the extra session with a three-point play for Detroit, and after Tari Phillips scored for New York, Nolan made it 85-81 with a 3-pointer. Ruth Riley fouled Phillips on two straight possessions, allowing New York to tie the score with 2:34 left. The score was deadlocked at 87 when Phillips was called for traveling with 35 seconds to go, setting up Nolan's clutch shot. Cheryl Ford added 17 for Detroit, and Swin Cash had 16. Vickie Johnson led New York with 23, and Phillips had a season-high 20 points and 10 rebounds. The score was tied at 44-all at halftime and stayed close throughout the second half. Detroit trailed 76-75 with two minutes left and had a chance to take the lead, but Nolan turned the ball over and Phillips scored at the other end. Riley's jumper pulled Detroit back within one, and both teams missed shots on their next possessions. Powell fouled Johnson with 28 seconds to go, and she split the free throws, making the score 79-77. Two seconds later, Robinson fouled Nolan, and she made both shots to tie the score. New York set up for the last shot, but Elena Baranova shot an airball with 0.2 seconds to play.

Game notes
The Detroit Demolition, newly crowned champions of the National Women's Football Association, attended the game and were honored at halftime. ... The Shock are the first team ever to sweep New York in a four-game season series. ... Both teams made 10 free throws in the first half, but the Shock missed eight while the Liberty were 10-for-10.
